[{"id":"VR725309","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a block on a horizontal surface with three points on the surface labeled A, B, and C from left to right. A wall is located to the left of the block and a spring in between connects the wall to the block. The block is held in place centered at point A.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR725309.g01.svg\"/></div></div></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">A block on a horizontal surface is attached to one end of a spring and the other end of the spring is attached to a fixed wall, as shown in the figure. The block is initially held in place with its center at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"A\"><math alttext=\"A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>A</mtext></math></span></span>. It is then released from rest and oscillates between points <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"A\"><math alttext=\"A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>A</mtext></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C\"><math alttext=\"C\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>C</mtext></math></span></span>. The block-spring system is in equilibrium when the center of the block is at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>B</mtext></math></span></span>, located halfway between points <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"A\"><math alttext=\"A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>A</mtext></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C\"><math alttext=\"C\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>C</mtext></math></span></span>. Later, the spring is replaced with a second spring of the same length but with a larger spring constant. This time the block is released from rest with its center to the left of Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"A\"><math alttext=\"A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>A</mtext></math></span></span>. Where is the center of the block relative to Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>B</mtext></math></span></span> when the new block-spring system is at equilibrium?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR725309_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">At Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>B</mtext></math></span></span></p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">To the left of Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>B</mtext></math></span></span></p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">To the right of Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>B</mtext></math></span></span></p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The new equilibrium position cannot be determined without more information about how much the spring constant and initial spring compression were changed.</p>"],"answer":0}]